1. The quadratically divergent part of the self-energy integral arises from the high-momentum ($k 	o \infty$) region of the loop. The integral is proportional to:
$$ \Pi_2^{\mu
u}(q) \propto \kappa^2 q_\alpha q_ eta \int^\Lambda \!  rac{d^4k}{(2\pi)^4}  rac{	ext{Tr}[\sigma^{\mu\alpha}\slashed{k}\sigma^{
u eta}\slashed{k}]}{k^4} $$
2. Expanding the trace gives $	ext{Tr}[\dots] = k_ho k_\sigma 	ext{Tr}[\sigma^{\mu\alpha}\gamma^ho \sigma^{
u eta}\gamma^\sigma]$. After symmetric integration over the loop momentum ($k_ho k_\sigma 	o  rac{1}{4}g_{ho\sigma}k^2$), the expression becomes proportional to the matrix trace $	ext{Tr}[\sigma^{\mu\alpha}\gamma_ho \sigma^{
u eta}\gamma^ho]$.
3. This trace is identically zero in four dimensions due to the Clifford algebra identity $\gamma_ho \sigma^{
u eta}\gamma^ho = 0$.
4. Consequently, the coefficient of the quadratic divergence is zero. The leading divergence is logarithmic, not quadratic. Thus, the quadratically divergent part is zero.
